    "synopsis": "[A] Genesis 6–9 records Noah's preservation through the flood in an ark, while [C] 1 Enoch 66 provides angelic commentary on the flood event, interpreting it through the lens of divine judgment and cosmic restoration. The chapter describes the angels showing Enoch the waters of judgment that will destroy the earth, explaining that these waters serve both to punish the wicked and to purify creation. [B] The ark becomes a type of salvation through judgment — a vessel of grace in the midst of wrath. [C] The Enochic tradition emphasizes that the flood was not merely a natural disaster but a deliberate undoing of creation, reversing the separation of waters in Genesis 1:6–10. The angels reveal that the flood waters come from both above (windows of heaven) and below (fountains of the deep), representing a cosmic collapse back toward pre-creation chaos. Yet Noah's preservation demonstrates God's commitment to maintaining a righteous remnant and continuing the human project despite corruption.",
    
